Observation: Both Test 1 and Test 2 were expected to produce different outcomes (Test 1 → rejected, Test 2 → approved), 
but the LLM returned rejected in both cases. The reason is that the submitted GitHub URLs could not be reliably accessed 
and verified by the LLM, causing it to default to a rejected verdict.

This is not a contract bug. The escrow logic, workflow, payment distribution, dispute process, and re-arbitration mechanisms all function correctly. 
The observed behavior is a limitation of the LLM when evaluating inaccessible or unverifiable URLs.


